{"title_page": "Revolut", "text_new": "{{short description|Financial technology company}}\n{{coi|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Revolut Ltd\n| logo = Revolut.png\n| logo size = \n| logo alt = \n| collapsible = <!-- \"yes\" or \"no\" -->\n| screenshot = \n| screenshot size = <!-- width in pixels, with \"px\" suffix -->\n| screenshot alt = \n| caption = \n| type = [[Private company|Private]]\n| traded as = \n| founded = {{start date and age|2015|07|01|df=yes}}<ref name=\"angellist-revolut\">{{cite web |url=https://angel.co/revolut | title=Revolut company profile | publisher=AngelList | accessdate=11 January 2016}}</ref>\n| dissolved = <!-- {{start date and age|year|month|day}} -->\n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| location = [[London]], England, UK\n| coordinates = \n| country of origin = \n| locations = \n| area served = \n| founder = Nikolay Storonsky, Vlad Yatsenko\n| president = \n| key_people = Nikolay Storonsky ([[Chief executive officer|CEO]])<br>Vladyslav Yatsenko ([[Chief technology officer|CTO]])\n| MD = \n| GM = \n| industry = [[FinTech]]\n| products = Current Accounts, Debit Cards, Insurance, Peer-to-peer lending, Remittance\n| services = Peer-to-peer payments, Currency Exchange\n| revenue = {{increase}} [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]158.24 million (2018)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://craft.co/revolut/revenue|title=Revolut revenue|publisher=Craft|accessdate=15 November 2019}}</ref>\n| operating income = \n| international = <!-- \"yes\" or \"no\" -->\n| net income = \n| assets = \n| owner = \n| num_employees = 1,596<ref>{{cite news|url=https://craft.co/revolut|title=Revolut Company Profile |publisher=Craft|accessdate=December 9, 2019}}</ref>\n| num_employees_year = 2019\n| parent = \n| divisions = \n| subsidiaries = \n| website = {{url|revolut.com}}\n| footnotes = \n}}\n\n'''Revolut Ltd''' is a British [[financial technology]] company that offers [[banking]] services including [[Pound sterling|GBP]] and [[Euro|EUR]] [[Bank account|bank accounts]], a [[MasterCard]] prepaid [[debit card]] or a [[VISA]] [[debit card]], fee-free [[Bureau de change|currency exchange]], stock trading, [[cryptocurrency]] exchange and [[peer-to-peer]] payments.<ref name=\"techcrunch1\">{{cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2015/07/20/revolut-raises-2-3-million-for-its-mobile-foreign-exchange-service/|title=Revolut Raises $2.3 Million For Its Mobile Foreign Exchange Service|author=Dillet|first=Romain|date=2015-07-20|website=[[TechCrunch]]|accessdate=2016-01-11}}</ref> The Revolut [[mobile app]] supports spending and [[automated teller machine|ATM]] withdrawals in 120 currencies and sending in 29 currencies directly from the app. It also provides customers access to [[Cryptocurrency|cryptocurrencies]] such as [[Bitcoin]] (BTC), [[Ethereum]] (ETH), [[Litecoin]] (LTC), [[Bitcoin Cash]] (BCH), and [[XRP]] by exchanging to or from 25 [[Fiat money|fiat currencies]]. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://techgarage.blog/en/banking-app-for-travelers-revolut-converts-currencies-minus-the-fees/|title=Banking App for Travelers \u2013 Revolut Converts Currencies Minus the Fees!|last=Kyburz|first=Kevin|date=2018-01-29|work=Techgarage|access-date=2018-02-11|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nThe company was founded in London by Nikolay Storonsky and Vlad Yatsenko. The company originally was based in Level39, a [[financial technology]] incubator in [[Canary Wharf]], [[London]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/consent/?toURL=https://www.forbes.com/sites/enriquedans/2018/04/29/are-you-ready-to-give-fintech-a-try/|title=Are You Ready To Give Fintech A Try?|last=Dan|first=Enriques|date=2018-04-29|website=[[Forbes]]|accessdate=2018-06-12}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Revolut app.jpg|thumb|An early edition of the Revolut app]]\nOn 26 April 2018, Revolut announced that it had raised a further $250 million in a funding round led by [[Hong Kong]]-based [[DST Global]], reaching a total valuation of $1.7 billion and thus becoming a [[Unicorn (finance)|unicorn]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/montymunford/2018/04/26/revolut-raises-250-million-at-1-7-billion-valuation-and-targets-100-million-users/|title=Revolut launches current accounts and a chatbot|last1=Munford|first1=Monty|date=2018-04-26|work=[[Forbes]]|accessdate=2018-04-26}}</ref> DST Global was founded by [[Yuri Milner]], who has been backed by the [[Kremlin]] in his previous investments.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/11/05/world/yuri-milner-facebook-twitter-russia.html|title=Kremlin Cash Behind Billionaire's Twitter and Facebook Investments|last=Drucker|first=Jesse|date=2017-11-05|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=2019-01-31|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2018, Revolut secured a [[Challenger bank|specialised bank]] licence from [[European Central Bank]], facilitated by the [[Bank of Lithuania]]. Having secured a specialised bank licence, Revolut is authorised to accept deposits and offer consumer credits. The main difference between a specialised and a full-range bank is that the former is not authorised to provide investment services. At the same time, an Electronic Money Institution licence was issued by the [[Bank of Lithuania]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lb.lt/en/news/revolut-granted-specialised-bank-and-electronic-money-institution-licences|title=Revolut granted specialised bank and electronic money institution licences|date=2018-12-13|website=Bank Of Lithuania|language=en|access-date=2018-12-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/989904f0-fe2c-11e8-aebf-99e208d3e521|title=Lithuania licence lets Revolut launch banking products|last=Megaw|first=Nicholas|date=2018-12-13|website=Financial Times|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-12-13}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2019, an expos\u00e9 of the company's employment practices and culture was published by [[Wired (magazine)|''Wired'']]. This found evidence of unpaid work, high staff turnover and employees being ordered to work weekends to meet [[performance indicator]]s.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/revolut-trade-unions-labour-fintech-politics-storonsky|title=Revolut insiders reveal the human cost of a fintech unicorn's wild rise|last=Mellino|first=Emiliano|date=2019-02-28|work=Wired|access-date=2019-03-01|language=en-UK}}</ref> A more recent article suggests that the company has responded to criticism and Revolut now has higher rating than its peers on Glassdoor.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sifted.eu/articles/challenger-banks-monzo-starling-revolut-n26-compared/|title=Digital banks Monzo, Revolut, Starling and N26 compared|website=Sifted|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-12-20}}</ref>\n\nIt was also revealed the company's Chief Financial Officer had quit, following allegations of compliance lapses.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://techcrunch.com/2019/03/01/revolut-cfo-peter-ohiggins-resigns//|title=Revolut CFO resigns following money laundering controversy|last=Russell|first=Joe|date=|work=[[TechCrunch]]|access-date=2019-03-01|language=en-UK}}</ref> This was denied by Revolut in a blog post.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.revolut.com/let-me-sec-the-record-straight/|title=Let me set the record straight|date=2019-03-01|website=Revolut Blog|access-date=2019-10-14}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2019 Revolut launched commission-free [[New York Stock Exchange]] & [[NASDAQ]] stocks trading within its app for customers in its \"Metal\" plan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/a50349ae-b3ac-11e9-bec9-fdcab53d6959|title=Subscribe to read|website=Financial Times|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-08-09}}</ref> Commission free trading has since been made available to all users.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.which.co.uk/news/2019/09/revolut-makes-stock-trading-free-for-all-customers-is-now-the-time-to-invest/|title=Should you trade stocks for free with Revolut?|website=Which? News|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-14}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2019, the company announced it was bringing in staff with more experience in traditional banking after critics suggested it was struggling to cope with its rapid growth. The hires included Wolfgang Bardorf, Treasurer and a former executive director at [[Goldman Sachs]] and the former global head of liquidity models and methodologies at [[Deutsche Bank]], Philip Doyle, director of financial crime risk who was previously head of financial crime at ClearBank and fraud prevention manager at [[Visa Inc.|Visa]], and Stefan Wille, deputy CFO who previously served as senior vice-president of finance at [[N26 (bank)|N26]] and corporate finance manager at [[Credit Suisse]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/a85c2904-c586-11e9-a8e9-296ca66511c9|title=Revolut bolsters senior team with banking executives|date=2019-08-23|website=FT|access-date=2019-11-16|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAs of December 2019, the company claimed to have 10 million users.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://twitter.com/ChadWestTweets/status/1205604753209774086|title=|last=|first=|date=2019-09-30|work=Reuters|access-date=2019-10-14|url-status=live|language=en}}</ref> \n\nIn October 2019 it was announced that the company will hire around 3,500 additional staff as it grows into 24 new markets owing to a new global deal with Visa.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.siliconrepublic.com/companies/revolut-visa-deal-fintech-markets|title=New deal with Visa will see Revolut hire thousands, expand into 24 markets|last=Short|first=Eva|date=2019-09-30|website=Silicon Republic|language=en|access-date=2019-10-07}}</ref> In October 2019 Revolut launched in [[Singapore]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Revolut opens for business in Singapore |url=https://www.cityam.com/revolut-opens-for-business-in-singapore/ |website=[[City A.M.]] |accessdate=24 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[Sky News]] reported in October 2019 that the company was looking to raise $1.5bn and had hired [[JPMorgan_Chase|JP Morgan]] to facilitate this. The fundraise would value Revolut between $5-10bn.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.sky.com/story/revolut-targets-1-5bn-to-join-fintech-elite-11833527|title=Revolut targets $1.5bn to join fintech elite|website=Sky News|language=en|access-date=2019-10-14}}</ref>\n\nRevolut became the UK's most valuable financial technology startup in February 2020 after a funding round that more than tripled its value. This comes after the company announced it had raised $500 million from a group of investors led by the US fund Technology Crossover Ventures.<ref>{{Cite news|last=correspondent|first=Kalyeena Makortoff Banking|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2020/feb/25/digital-bank-revolut-becomes-uk-most-valuable-fintech-startup-cash-injection-airbnb-spotify|title=Digital bank Revolut becomes UK's most valuable fintech startup|date=2020-02-25|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-02-25|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://business.devilhunter.net/2020/02/revolut-raises-500-million-for-55.html |website=Zinios |title=Revolut raises $ 500 million for a $ 5.5 billion company valuation |language=en |accessdate=February 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Founder==\nNikolay Storonsky [[Founder CEO|founded]] Revolut. He is a [[United Kingdom|British]]-[[Russia]]n [[entrepreneur]].<ref>{{Cite web|\nurl=https://www.businessinsider.com/fintech-unicorn-revolut-forced-to-deny-russian-links-in-lithuania-2019-2|title=UK fintech unicorn Revolut forced to deny links to Russia|last=Burroughs|first=Callum|website=Business Insider|access-date=2019-04-29}}</ref><ref name=\"cityam\">{{Cite web|\nurl=http://www.cityam.com/273560/fintech-startup-revolut-pushes-ministers-fast-track-tech|title=Revolut pushes ministers for fast-track tech visas|last=Nicolle|first=Emily|date=2019-02-21|website=www.cityam.com|language=en|access-date=2019-04-29}}</ref><ref name=\"telegraph\">{{Cite news|\nurl=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2018/04/10/revolut-boss-nikolay-storonsky-never-seen-big-bank-do-something/|title=Revolut boss Nikolay Storonsky: \u2018I\u2019ve never seen a big bank do something cool \u2013 if they did, we wouldn\u2019t exist\u2019|last=Smith|first=Edwin|date=2018-04-10|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2019-04-29|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref><ref name=\"FT\">{{cite web|\nurl=https://www.ft.com/content/6f26d10a-051d-11e8-9650-9c0ad2d7c5b5|title=Revolut\u2019s Nikolay Storonsky on long hours and high staff turnover|author=Kadhim Shubber |work=[[Financial Times]]|date=2018-02-18|accessdate=2018-03-13}}</ref><ref name=\"BI\">{{cite web|\nurl=http://www.businessinsider.com/interview-revolut-nikolay-storonsky-culture-rapid-growth-2017-10|title=Our culture is 'about getting s**t done': The Revolut founder on why his people work 12-13 hours a day|author=Oscar Williams-Grut |work=[[Business Insider]]|date=2017-10-13|accessdate=2018-03-13}}</ref> He studied for a master's degree in physics at [[Moscow Institute of Physics and Technology]], and during this time became a state champion swimmer.<ref name=ft>{{cite web|title=Revolut\u2019s Nikolay Storonsky on long hours and high staff turnover|url=https://www.ft.com/content/6f26d10a-051d-11e8-9650-9c0ad2d7c5b5|website=[[Financial Times]]|accessdate=16 May 2018}}</ref> He completed a separate masters in economics at [[New Economic School]] in [[Moscow]].<ref name=\"ft\"/> Prior to founding Revolut, Storonsky was a [[Financial trade|trader]] at [[Credit Suisse]] and [[Lehman Brothers]].<ref name=\"revolut-deck\">{{cite web|url=http://www.slideshare.net/NikolayStoronsky/revolut-deck-140115|title=Revolut Deck|publisher=[[SlideShare]]|date=2015-01-14|accessdate=2016-09-11}}</ref>  Alongside Vlad Yatsenko, former [[Credit Suisse]] and [[Deutsche Bank]] developer, Storonsky set up Revolut and raised around $3.5 million,<ref name=\"forbes-interview\" /> saying in an interview with Forbes: {{Quote|text=I thought of the business three years ago. I was travelling a lot and wasting hundreds of pounds on foreign transaction fees and exchange rate commissions which just didn\u2019t feel right. As someone with a financial background I knew exactly the rates I should be getting. As a solution, I tried to find a multi-currency card and was later told it wasn\u2019t possible. But I was determined to make it work.<ref name=\"forbes-interview\">{{cite web|last1=Salter|first1=Philip|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/philipsalter/2015/12/09/london-fintech-entrepreneur-talking-about-a-revolution/|website=Forbes|title=London Fintech Entrepreneur Talking About A Revolution}}</ref>}}\n\nHis father Nikolay Mironovich Storonsky<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.delfi.lt/a/80164183|title=LRT: \u043e\u0442\u0435\u0446 \u0433\u043b\u0430\u0432\u044b Revolut \u0421\u0442\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0440\u0430\u0431\u043e\u0442\u0430\u0435\u0442 \u0432 \"\u0413\u0430\u0437\u043f\u0440\u043e\u043c\u0435\"|last=BNS|website=DELFI|access-date=2019-03-27}}</ref> is Deputy [[General Director]] of Science for [[Gazprom Promgaz]] since 2017, and First Deputy General Director for Science [[Gazprom Promgaz]] OAO.<ref>[https://www.bloomberg.com/profiles/people/16656234-nikolay-storonsky Nikolay Mironovich Storonsky] ([[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]] info)</ref>\n\n== Automated suspension of accounts ==\n\nRevolut, in common with traditional financial institutions, uses algorithms to identify [[money laundering]], fraud and other criminal activity, but unlike the rest of the banking industry, Revolut's algorithms additionally trigger the automated suspension of accounts. Revolut explains that \"the system is programmed to temporarily lock an account and place it in a queue, until one of our compliance agents can review the case\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Braileanu |first1=Rob |title=Why has my account been locked and how to regain access? |url=https://blog.revolut.com/why-has-my-account-been-locked-and-how-to-regain-access/ |website=Revolut |publisher=Revolut Ltd |accessdate=23 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nIt is increasingly reported that Revolut's algorithms suspend a growing number of accounts in error for weeks or months at a time because Revolut does not have sufficient ''compliance agents'' to review the automated suspensions, and that while Revolut pays no interest on the large suspended balances, Revolut can earn interest on the funds in wholesale [[money markets]]. Customers whose accounts are suspended are blocked from contacting Revolut's usual support channel and instead receive automated responses from a [[chatbot]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Marks |first1=Oliver |title=Revolut\u2019s clumsy automated bank compliance results in frozen accounts and lack of customer service |url=https://www.zdnet.com/article/revoluts-clumsy-automated-fintech-bank-compliance-results-in-frozen-accounts-and-lack-of-customer-service/ |accessdate=23 February 2020 |work=ZDNet |publisher= CBS Interactive |date=17 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Barker |first1=Sam |title=Revolut customers locked out of accounts 'for weeks' |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/personal-banking/current-accounts/revolut-customers-locked-accounts-weeks/ |accessdate=23 February 2020 |work=The Telegraph |publisher=The Daily Telegraph |date=21 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Palmer |first1=Kate |title=Monzo and Revolut: customer complaints are mounting at digital banks |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/monzo-and-revolut-customer-complaints-are-mounting-at-digital-banks-p9fm3xjmj |accessdate=23 February 2020 |work=The Times |publisher=The Times |date=8 February 2020}}</ref> The [[Daily Telegraph]] reported that Revolut suspended an account containing \u00a390,000 for more than two months<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hunt |first1=Marianna |title=Revolut could face lawsuit from customers locked out of their accounts |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/money/consumer-affairs/revolut-could-face-lawsuit-customers-locked-accounts/ |accessdate=23 February 2020 |work= The Telegraph |publisher= The Daily Telegraph |date=25 January 2000}}</ref> and that another customer travelled 500 miles from [[Auvergne]] in France to Revolut's London offices in an unsuccessful attempt to recover \u00a315,000 in an account that Revolut had similarly frozen in error.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hunt |first1=Marianna |title=Ex-UCL lecturer forced to travel to London from France in attempts to unblock digital bank account |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2020/01/24/ex-ucl-lecturer-forced-travel-london-france-attempts-unblock/ |accessdate=27 February 2020 |work=The Telegraph |publisher=The Daily Telegraph |date=24 January 2020}}</ref> In a further case reported by [[The Times]], Revolut suspended and subsequently closed a business account containing \u20ac300,000 belonging to Priorit\u00e9 Energie, which \"''helps low-income families in Paris to insulate their homes under a government initiative''\", preventing the company from paying its staff.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dunkley |first1=Emma |title=Nikolay Storonsky\u2019s Revolut freezes accounts in money-laundering bungle |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/nikolay-storonskys-revolut-freezes-accounts-in-money-laundering-bungle-5nt3lv6zk |accessdate=23 February 2020 |work=The Times |publisher=The Times |date=23 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website}}\n\n[[Category:Foreign exchange companies]]\n[[Category:Digital currency exchanges]]\n[[Category:Financial services companies of the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Financial technology company}}\n{{coi|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Revolut Ltd\n| logo = Revolut.png\n| logo size = \n| logo alt = \n| collapsible = <!-- \"yes\" or \"no\" -->\n| screenshot = \n| screenshot size = <!-- width in pixels, with \"px\" suffix -->\n| screenshot alt = \n| caption = \n| type = [[Private company|Private]]\n| traded as = \n| founded = {{start date and age|2015|07|01|df=yes}}<ref name=\"angellist-revolut\">{{cite web |url=https://angel.co/revolut | title=Revolut company profile | publisher=AngelList | accessdate=11 January 2016}}</ref>\n| dissolved = <!-- {{start date and age|year|month|day}} -->\n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| location = [[London]], England, UK\n| coordinates = \n| country of origin = \n| locations = \n| area served = \n| founder = Nikolay Storonsky, Vlad Yatsenko\n| president = \n| key_people = Nikolay Storonsky ([[Chief executive officer|CEO]])<br>Vladyslav Yatsenko ([[Chief technology officer|CTO]])\n| MD = \n| GM = \n| industry = [[FinTech]]\n| products = Current Accounts, Debit Cards, Insurance, Peer-to-peer lending, Remittance\n| services = Peer-to-peer payments, Currency Exchange\n| revenue = {{increase}} [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]58.24 million (2018)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://craft.co/revolut/revenue|title=Revolut revenue|publisher=Craft|accessdate=15 November 2019}}</ref>\n| operating income = \n| international = <!-- \"yes\" or \"no\" -->\n| net income = \n| assets = \n| owner = \n| num_employees = 1,596<ref>{{cite news|url=https://craft.co/revolut|title=Revolut Company Profile |publisher=Craft|accessdate=December 9, 2019}}</ref>\n| num_employees_year = 2019\n| parent = \n| divisions = \n| subsidiaries = \n| website = {{url|revolut.com}}\n| footnotes = \n}}\n\n'''Revolut Ltd''' is a British [[financial technology]] company that offers [[banking]] services including [[Pound sterling|GBP]] and [[Euro|EUR]] [[Bank account|bank accounts]], a [[MasterCard]] prepaid [[debit card]] or a [[VISA]] [[debit card]], fee-free [[Bureau de change|currency exchange]], stock trading, [[cryptocurrency]] exchange and [[peer-to-peer]] payments.<ref name=\"techcrunch1\">{{cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2015/07/20/revolut-raises-2-3-million-for-its-mobile-foreign-exchange-service/|title=Revolut Raises $2.3 Million For Its Mobile Foreign Exchange Service|author=Dillet|first=Romain|date=2015-07-20|website=[[TechCrunch]]|accessdate=2016-01-11}}</ref> The Revolut [[mobile app]] supports spending and [[automated teller machine|ATM]] withdrawals in 120 currencies and sending in 29 currencies directly from the app. It also provides customers access to [[Cryptocurrency|cryptocurrencies]] such as [[Bitcoin]] (BTC), [[Ethereum]] (ETH), [[Litecoin]] (LTC), [[Bitcoin Cash]] (BCH), and [[XRP]] by exchanging to or from 25 [[Fiat money|fiat currencies]]. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://techgarage.blog/en/banking-app-for-travelers-revolut-converts-currencies-minus-the-fees/|title=Banking App for Travelers \u2013 Revolut Converts Currencies Minus the Fees!|last=Kyburz|first=Kevin|date=2018-01-29|work=Techgarage|access-date=2018-02-11|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nThe company was founded in London by Nikolay Storonsky and Vlad Yatsenko. The company originally was based in Level39, a [[financial technology]] incubator in [[Canary Wharf]], [[London]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/consent/?toURL=https://www.forbes.com/sites/enriquedans/2018/04/29/are-you-ready-to-give-fintech-a-try/|title=Are You Ready To Give Fintech A Try?|last=Dan|first=Enriques|date=2018-04-29|website=[[Forbes]]|accessdate=2018-06-12}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Revolut app.jpg|thumb|An early edition of the Revolut app]]\nOn 26 April 2018, Revolut announced that it had raised a further $250 million in a funding round led by [[Hong Kong]]-based [[DST Global]], reaching a total valuation of $1.7 billion and thus becoming a [[Unicorn (finance)|unicorn]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/montymunford/2018/04/26/revolut-raises-250-million-at-1-7-billion-valuation-and-targets-100-million-users/|title=Revolut launches current accounts and a chatbot|last1=Munford|first1=Monty|date=2018-04-26|work=[[Forbes]]|accessdate=2018-04-26}}</ref> DST Global was founded by [[Yuri Milner]], who has been backed by the [[Kremlin]] in his previous investments.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/11/05/world/yuri-milner-facebook-twitter-russia.html|title=Kremlin Cash Behind Billionaire's Twitter and Facebook Investments|last=Drucker|first=Jesse|date=2017-11-05|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=2019-01-31|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2018, Revolut secured a [[Challenger bank|specialised bank]] licence from [[European Central Bank]], facilitated by the [[Bank of Lithuania]]. Having secured a specialised bank licence, Revolut is authorised to accept deposits and offer consumer credits. The main difference between a specialised and a full-range bank is that the former is not authorised to provide investment services. At the same time, an Electronic Money Institution licence was issued by the [[Bank of Lithuania]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lb.lt/en/news/revolut-granted-specialised-bank-and-electronic-money-institution-licences|title=Revolut granted specialised bank and electronic money institution licences|date=2018-12-13|website=Bank Of Lithuania|language=en|access-date=2018-12-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/989904f0-fe2c-11e8-aebf-99e208d3e521|title=Lithuania licence lets Revolut launch banking products|last=Megaw|first=Nicholas|date=2018-12-13|website=Financial Times|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-12-13}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2019, an expos\u00e9 of the company's employment practices and culture was published by [[Wired (magazine)|''Wired'']]. This found evidence of unpaid work, high staff turnover and employees being ordered to work weekends to meet [[performance indicator]]s.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/revolut-trade-unions-labour-fintech-politics-storonsky|title=Revolut insiders reveal the human cost of a fintech unicorn's wild rise|last=Mellino|first=Emiliano|date=2019-02-28|work=Wired|access-date=2019-03-01|language=en-UK}}</ref> A more recent article suggests that the company has responded to criticism and Revolut now has higher rating than its peers on Glassdoor.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sifted.eu/articles/challenger-banks-monzo-starling-revolut-n26-compared/|title=Digital banks Monzo, Revolut, Starling and N26 compared|website=Sifted|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-12-20}}</ref>\n\nIt was also revealed the company's Chief Financial Officer had quit, following allegations of compliance lapses.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://techcrunch.com/2019/03/01/revolut-cfo-peter-ohiggins-resigns//|title=Revolut CFO resigns following money laundering controversy|last=Russell|first=Joe|date=|work=[[TechCrunch]]|access-date=2019-03-01|language=en-UK}}</ref> This was denied by Revolut in a blog post.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.revolut.com/let-me-sec-the-record-straight/|title=Let me set the record straight|date=2019-03-01|website=Revolut Blog|access-date=2019-10-14}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2019 Revolut launched commission-free [[New York Stock Exchange]] & [[NASDAQ]] stocks trading within its app for customers in its \"Metal\" plan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/a50349ae-b3ac-11e9-bec9-fdcab53d6959|title=Subscribe to read|website=Financial Times|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-08-09}}</ref> Commission free trading has since been made available to all users.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.which.co.uk/news/2019/09/revolut-makes-stock-trading-free-for-all-customers-is-now-the-time-to-invest/|title=Should you trade stocks for free with Revolut?|website=Which? News|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-14}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2019, the company announced it was bringing in staff with more experience in traditional banking after critics suggested it was struggling to cope with its rapid growth. The hires included Wolfgang Bardorf, Treasurer and a former executive director at [[Goldman Sachs]] and the former global head of liquidity models and methodologies at [[Deutsche Bank]], Philip Doyle, director of financial crime risk who was previously head of financial crime at ClearBank and fraud prevention manager at [[Visa Inc.|Visa]], and Stefan Wille, deputy CFO who previously served as senior vice-president of finance at [[N26 (bank)|N26]] and corporate finance manager at [[Credit Suisse]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/a85c2904-c586-11e9-a8e9-296ca66511c9|title=Revolut bolsters senior team with banking executives|date=2019-08-23|website=FT|access-date=2019-11-16|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAs of December 2019, the company claimed to have 10 million users.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://twitter.com/ChadWestTweets/status/1205604753209774086|title=|last=|first=|date=2019-09-30|work=Reuters|access-date=2019-10-14|url-status=live|language=en}}</ref> \n\nIn October 2019 it was announced that the company will hire around 3,500 additional staff as it grows into 24 new markets owing to a new global deal with Visa.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.siliconrepublic.com/companies/revolut-visa-deal-fintech-markets|title=New deal with Visa will see Revolut hire thousands, expand into 24 markets|last=Short|first=Eva|date=2019-09-30|website=Silicon Republic|language=en|access-date=2019-10-07}}</ref> In October 2019 Revolut launched in [[Singapore]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Revolut opens for business in Singapore |url=https://www.cityam.com/revolut-opens-for-business-in-singapore/ |website=[[City A.M.]] |accessdate=24 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[Sky News]] reported in October 2019 that the company was looking to raise $1.5bn and had hired [[JPMorgan_Chase|JP Morgan]] to facilitate this. The fundraise would value Revolut between $5-10bn.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.sky.com/story/revolut-targets-1-5bn-to-join-fintech-elite-11833527|title=Revolut targets $1.5bn to join fintech elite|website=Sky News|language=en|access-date=2019-10-14}}</ref>\n\nRevolut became the UK's most valuable financial technology startup in February 2020 after a funding round that more than tripled its value. This comes after the company announced it had raised $500 million from a group of investors led by the US fund Technology Crossover Ventures.<ref>{{Cite news|last=correspondent|first=Kalyeena Makortoff Banking|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2020/feb/25/digital-bank-revolut-becomes-uk-most-valuable-fintech-startup-cash-injection-airbnb-spotify|title=Digital bank Revolut becomes UK's most valuable fintech startup|date=2020-02-25|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-02-25|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://business.devilhunter.net/2020/02/revolut-raises-500-million-for-55.html |website=Zinios |title=Revolut raises $ 500 million for a $ 5.5 billion company valuation |language=en |accessdate=February 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Founder==\nNikolay Storonsky [[Founder CEO|founded]] Revolut. He is a [[United Kingdom|British]]-[[Russia]]n [[entrepreneur]].<ref>{{Cite web|\nurl=https://www.businessinsider.com/fintech-unicorn-revolut-forced-to-deny-russian-links-in-lithuania-2019-2|title=UK fintech unicorn Revolut forced to deny links to Russia|last=Burroughs|first=Callum|website=Business Insider|access-date=2019-04-29}}</ref><ref name=\"cityam\">{{Cite web|\nurl=http://www.cityam.com/273560/fintech-startup-revolut-pushes-ministers-fast-track-tech|title=Revolut pushes ministers for fast-track tech visas|last=Nicolle|first=Emily|date=2019-02-21|website=www.cityam.com|language=en|access-date=2019-04-29}}</ref><ref name=\"telegraph\">{{Cite news|\nurl=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2018/04/10/revolut-boss-nikolay-storonsky-never-seen-big-bank-do-something/|title=Revolut boss Nikolay Storonsky: \u2018I\u2019ve never seen a big bank do something cool \u2013 if they did, we wouldn\u2019t exist\u2019|last=Smith|first=Edwin|date=2018-04-10|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2019-04-29|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref><ref name=\"FT\">{{cite web|\nurl=https://www.ft.com/content/6f26d10a-051d-11e8-9650-9c0ad2d7c5b5|title=Revolut\u2019s Nikolay Storonsky on long hours and high staff turnover|author=Kadhim Shubber |work=[[Financial Times]]|date=2018-02-18|accessdate=2018-03-13}}</ref><ref name=\"BI\">{{cite web|\nurl=http://www.businessinsider.com/interview-revolut-nikolay-storonsky-culture-rapid-growth-2017-10|title=Our culture is 'about getting s**t done': The Revolut founder on why his people work 12-13 hours a day|author=Oscar Williams-Grut |work=[[Business Insider]]|date=2017-10-13|accessdate=2018-03-13}}</ref> He studied for a master's degree in physics at [[Moscow Institute of Physics and Technology]], and during this time became a state champion swimmer.<ref name=ft>{{cite web|title=Revolut\u2019s Nikolay Storonsky on long hours and high staff turnover|url=https://www.ft.com/content/6f26d10a-051d-11e8-9650-9c0ad2d7c5b5|website=[[Financial Times]]|accessdate=16 May 2018}}</ref> He completed a separate masters in economics at [[New Economic School]] in [[Moscow]].<ref name=\"ft\"/> Prior to founding Revolut, Storonsky was a [[Financial trade|trader]] at [[Credit Suisse]] and [[Lehman Brothers]].<ref name=\"revolut-deck\">{{cite web|url=http://www.slideshare.net/NikolayStoronsky/revolut-deck-140115|title=Revolut Deck|publisher=[[SlideShare]]|date=2015-01-14|accessdate=2016-09-11}}</ref>  Alongside Vlad Yatsenko, former [[Credit Suisse]] and [[Deutsche Bank]] developer, Storonsky set up Revolut and raised around $3.5 million,<ref name=\"forbes-interview\" /> saying in an interview with Forbes: {{Quote|text=I thought of the business three years ago. I was travelling a lot and wasting hundreds of pounds on foreign transaction fees and exchange rate commissions which just didn\u2019t feel right. As someone with a financial background I knew exactly the rates I should be getting. As a solution, I tried to find a multi-currency card and was later told it wasn\u2019t possible. But I was determined to make it work.<ref name=\"forbes-interview\">{{cite web|last1=Salter|first1=Philip|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/philipsalter/2015/12/09/london-fintech-entrepreneur-talking-about-a-revolution/|website=Forbes|title=London Fintech Entrepreneur Talking About A Revolution}}</ref>}}\n\nHis father Nikolay Mironovich Storonsky<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.delfi.lt/a/80164183|title=LRT: \u043e\u0442\u0435\u0446 \u0433\u043b\u0430\u0432\u044b Revolut \u0421\u0442\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0440\u0430\u0431\u043e\u0442\u0430\u0435\u0442 \u0432 \"\u0413\u0430\u0437\u043f\u0440\u043e\u043c\u0435\"|last=BNS|website=DELFI|access-date=2019-03-27}}</ref> is Deputy [[General Director]] of Science for [[Gazprom Promgaz]] since 2017, and First Deputy General Director for Science [[Gazprom Promgaz]] OAO.<ref>[https://www.bloomberg.com/profiles/people/16656234-nikolay-storonsky Nikolay Mironovich Storonsky] ([[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]] info)</ref>\n\n== Automated suspension of accounts ==\n\nRevolut, in common with traditional financial institutions, uses algorithms to identify [[money laundering]], fraud and other criminal activity, but unlike the rest of the banking industry, Revolut's algorithms additionally trigger the automated suspension of accounts. Revolut explains that \"the system is programmed to temporarily lock an account and place it in a queue, until one of our compliance agents can review the case\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Braileanu |first1=Rob |title=Why has my account been locked and how to regain access? |url=https://blog.revolut.com/why-has-my-account-been-locked-and-how-to-regain-access/ |website=Revolut |publisher=Revolut Ltd |accessdate=23 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nIt is increasingly reported that Revolut's algorithms suspend a growing number of accounts in error for weeks or months at a time because Revolut does not have sufficient ''compliance agents'' to review the automated suspensions, and that while Revolut pays no interest on the large suspended balances, Revolut can earn interest on the funds in wholesale [[money markets]]. Customers whose accounts are suspended are blocked from contacting Revolut's usual support channel and instead receive automated responses from a [[chatbot]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Marks |first1=Oliver |title=Revolut\u2019s clumsy automated bank compliance results in frozen accounts and lack of customer service |url=https://www.zdnet.com/article/revoluts-clumsy-automated-fintech-bank-compliance-results-in-frozen-accounts-and-lack-of-customer-service/ |accessdate=23 February 2020 |work=ZDNet |publisher= CBS Interactive |date=17 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Barker |first1=Sam |title=Revolut customers locked out of accounts 'for weeks' |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/personal-banking/current-accounts/revolut-customers-locked-accounts-weeks/ |accessdate=23 February 2020 |work=The Telegraph |publisher=The Daily Telegraph |date=21 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Palmer |first1=Kate |title=Monzo and Revolut: customer complaints are mounting at digital banks |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/monzo-and-revolut-customer-complaints-are-mounting-at-digital-banks-p9fm3xjmj |accessdate=23 February 2020 |work=The Times |publisher=The Times |date=8 February 2020}}</ref> The [[Daily Telegraph]] reported that Revolut suspended an account containing \u00a390,000 for more than two months<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hunt |first1=Marianna |title=Revolut could face lawsuit from customers locked out of their accounts |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/money/consumer-affairs/revolut-could-face-lawsuit-customers-locked-accounts/ |accessdate=23 February 2020 |work= The Telegraph |publisher= The Daily Telegraph |date=25 January 2000}}</ref> and that another customer travelled 500 miles from [[Auvergne]] in France to Revolut's London offices in an unsuccessful attempt to recover \u00a315,000 in an account that Revolut had similarly frozen in error.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hunt |first1=Marianna |title=Ex-UCL lecturer forced to travel to London from France in attempts to unblock digital bank account |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2020/01/24/ex-ucl-lecturer-forced-travel-london-france-attempts-unblock/ |accessdate=27 February 2020 |work=The Telegraph |publisher=The Daily Telegraph |date=24 January 2020}}</ref> In a further case reported by [[The Times]], Revolut suspended and subsequently closed a business account containing \u20ac300,000 belonging to Priorit\u00e9 Energie, which \"''helps low-income families in Paris to insulate their homes under a government initiative''\", preventing the company from paying its staff.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dunkley |first1=Emma |title=Nikolay Storonsky\u2019s Revolut freezes accounts in money-laundering bungle |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/nikolay-storonskys-revolut-freezes-accounts-in-money-laundering-bungle-5nt3lv6zk |accessdate=23 February 2020 |work=The Times |publisher=The Times |date=23 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website}}\n\n[[Category:Foreign exchange companies]]\n[[Category:Digital currency exchanges]]\n[[Category:Financial services companies of the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "185.72.224.212", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Revolut"}
